<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>ELECTRICAL SYSTEM TROUBLESHOOTING GUIDE - 9800 - SINGLE REDUCTION, SINGLE SPEED AXLES: SPICER D135-S,
        F155-S, F170-S SERIES - PINION POSITION - Pinion Position
    </stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="adjust" graphiccount="6">
        <title>Pinion Position</title>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">To establish the correct nominal dimension by using a pinion setting gauge, install pinion
                gear, and cage assembly into the carrier housing. Tighten bolt to 160 to 180 ft-lbs (217 to 244 N&#8226;m).
                Failure to tighten properly may result in incorrect gear adjustment.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Attach the step plate clamp assembly to the carrier mounting flange. Locate step plate clamp
                screw over center of pinion gear. Install step plate under clamp screw and tighten to hold step plate
                securely in position (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1401454">Figure 54</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1401454" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1401454" filename="../figg14/g1401454.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 54. Step Plate Clamp Assembly Installation</caption>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Be sure lugs on bottom of step plate straddle the bearing staking indentations on end of
                        pinion, or false reading may occur. Also, make sure differential side bearing bores are clean
                        and free of nicks.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove any burrs and wipe clean differential bearing bore l.D.s. Turn micrometer 90&#176; to
                step plate. Install assembled pinion setting gauge into bearing bores of carrier housing. Adjust
                micrometer so it is directly over end of step plate. Run the micrometer thimble down to measure the
                distance between the center of the ring gear and the step plate (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1401455">Figure 55</hotlnk>).
                <emph type="bold">Make a note of this dimension.</emph>
            </para>
            <figure id="f1401455" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1401455" filename="../figg14/g1401455.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 55. Measure Distance Between Center Ring and Step Plate</caption>
            </figure>
            <para>
                <emph type="bold">Because the step plate must be taken into consideration, the thickness of the step
                    plate [.400 inch (10.16 mm) ] needs to be added to the measured value for the correct micrometer
                    distance.
                </emph>
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">On the machined end of each pinion gear is etched either a plus (+) number, a minus (-)
                number or a zero (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1401456">Figure 56</hotlnk>). This number represents the amount in thousandths of an
                inch (.001) to be added (+) or subtracted (-) from the nominal dimension for the best running position
                for that particular gear set.
            </para>
            <figure id="f1401456" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1401456" filename="../figg14/g1401456.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 56. Matched Set Number</caption>
            </figure>
            <para>EXAMPLE: If pinion is etched +3, the required mounting distance is more than nominal by .003 in. (.076
                mm). This means the pinion would require .003 in. (.076 mm) thicker shim between pinion bearing cage
                assembly and carrier housing than a pinion etched with "0".
            </para>
        </step1>
        <para>If the pinion is marked -3, the shim required between pinion bearing cage assembly and carrier housing
            would be .003 in. (.076 mm) thinner than if pinion was etched "0".
        </para>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">The following two examples illustrate how proper running position is achieved by computing
                dimensions you have obtained.
            </para>
        </step1>
